    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Gore and Bush, Navigating the 60's</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John C Grannis letter sees hypocrisy in Al Gore's decision to serve in Vietnam even though he recognized war's evil</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your June 21 front-page article portrays Al Gore's decision to serve in Vietnam as a moral judgment. What choice did the boys back in Tennessee have, Mr. Gore reasoned. We all had a choice, no matter what our state or station. Like Mr. Gore, many of us saw the evil of the Vietnam War, but unlike him, we refused to cooperate, on moral grounds.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your June 21 front-page article portrays Al Gore's decision to serve in Vietnam as a moral judgment. What choice did the boys back in Tennessee have, Mr. Gore reasoned. We all had a choice, no matter what our state or station. Like Mr. Gore, many of us saw the evil of the Vietnam War, but unlike him, we refused to cooperate, on moral grounds.</p>
        <p>Mr. Gore chose to do what was expected of him. When a person sees the morally correct path but chooses the other, there's a word for it. It's called hypocrisy.</p>
        <p>JOHN C. GRANNIS  Montclair, N.J., June 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
